   "id": "da23a97b-39f4-4b43-b014-10ab908fb3b9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Background Info\n",
    "\n",
    "Along with this project is a data file:\n",
    "nyc_parking_tickets_extract.csv\n",
    "\n",
    "Summons No, Plate ID, Registration State, Plate Type, Issue Date, Violation Code, Vehicle Body Type, Vehicle Make, Violation Description\n",
    "\n",
    "-> fields separated by commas\n",
    "-> first row contains field names\n",
    "-> data rows are a mix of data types: string, date, int\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that end-of-line char is not visible but its there"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8e923c12-2081-46df-8a4e-a927a4ec9386",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Goal 1\n",
    "\n",
    "Your first goal is to create a lazy iterator that will produce a named tuple for each row of data\n",
    "The contents of each tuple should be an appropriate data type (e.g. date, int, string)\n",
    "You can use the split method for string to split on the comma\n",
    "You will need to use the strip method to remove the end of line char (\\n)\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember the goal is to produce a lazy iterator\n",
    "-> you should not be reading entire file in memory and processing it\n",
    "-> goal is to keep the required memory overhead to a minimum\n",
    "Please stick to Python's built-ins and standard library only"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "45141bef-a9ce-4950-9253-8272931dfea6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Goal 2\n",
    "\n",
    "Calculate the number of violations by car make\n",
    "Use the lazy iterator you created in Goal 1\n",
    "Use lazy evaluation whenever possible\n",
    "You can choose otherwise but store make and violation counts as a dictionary\n",
    "-> key = car make\n",
    "-> value = # violations"
   ]
  },
